<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,260,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Comments:</emphasis>
The presence of ocelli and a frenulum with three acanthi are all typical female characters in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak &amp; Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[151,274,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tortricinae">Tortricinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[329,455,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[471,635,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
); in females of Chlidanotini and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Diakonoff" authorityYear="1977" box="[1006,1174,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hilarographini">Hilarographini</taxonomicName>
, the two other tribes of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,311,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
, the frenulum usually has only two acanthi (
<bibRefCitation author="Yang, A. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[831,1080,332,356]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="743 - 751" refId="ref14743" refString="Yang, A. &amp; Brown, J. W. (2009) Variation in the female frenulum in Tortricidae (Lepidoptera). Part 1. Chlidanotinae. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 111, 743 - 751. https: // doi. org / 10.4289 / 0013 - 8797 - 111.3.743" type="journal article" year="2009">Yang &amp; Brown 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The chaetosemata, which are highly characteristic of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[416,538,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
and lacking in similar microlepidoptera, are not visible. Two rows of scales and extremely short sensory setae of the antenna are key features of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Horak &amp; Brown 1991)" authorityName="Horak &amp; Brown" authorityYear="1991" baseAuthorityName="Horak &amp; Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[874,1273,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tortricinae">
Tortricinae (
<bibRefCitation author="Horak, M. &amp; Brown, R. L." box="[1012,1264,404,429]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="23 - 48" refId="ref12775" refString="Horak, M. &amp; Brown, R. L. (1991) 1.2 Taxonomy and phylogeny. In: van der Geest, L. P. S. &amp; Evenhuis, H. H. (Eds.), Tortricid pests, their biology, natural enemies and control. Elsevier Science Publishers B. V., Amsterdam, pp. 23 - 48." type="book chapter" year="1991">Horak &amp; Brown 1991</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The forewing venation is characteristic of many 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pierce &amp; Metcalfe" authorityYear="1922" box="[547,655,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Archipini">Archipini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[713,842,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
, and the hindwing venation does not contradict this assignment. The slightly sinuate costa of the hindwing with a concave region preapically (
<figureCitation box="[1174,1246,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1522,1544]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,266,1499]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1434,265,1500]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antiquatortia histuroides Brown &amp; Baixeras, gen. nov., sp. nov. AMNH DR8-43. Dominican amber. a. Ventral view. Length of forewing 7 mm. b. Wing venation c. Dorsal view of forewing with tufts of erect scales. d. Papillae anales. Photos: Mark Metz. Illustration: Joaquin Baixeras." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3094741/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Figs 2</figureCitation>
a–b) is a feature that is found in many 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pierce &amp; Metcalfe" authorityYear="1922" box="[406,516,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Archipini">Archipini</taxonomicName>
, a few 
<taxonomicName box="[602,759,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Sparganothini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sparganothini</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Clemens, 1860" authorityName="Clemens" authorityYear="1860" box="[833,1114,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Amorbia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[833,931,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Amorbia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Clemens, B." box="[940,1114,511,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="345 - 362" refId="ref11991" refString="Clemens, B. (1860) Contributions to American Lepidopterology. No. 6. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 12, 345 - 362." type="journal article" year="1860">Clemens, 1860</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), and many Eucosmini. The patches of raised scales are typical of 
<taxonomicName box="[614,719,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Tortricini">Tortricini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[785,914,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
, although present in a few genera scattered throughout the family (
<figureCitation box="[409,496,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1522,1544]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,266,1499]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1434,265,1500]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antiquatortia histuroides Brown &amp; Baixeras, gen. nov., sp. nov. AMNH DR8-43. Dominican amber. a. Ventral view. Length of forewing 7 mm. b. Wing venation c. Dorsal view of forewing with tufts of erect scales. d. Papillae anales. Photos: Mark Metz. Illustration: Joaquin Baixeras." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3094741/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Fig. 2 c</figureCitation>
). The papillae anales are weak, but they appear to be flat as in most tortricids (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1522,1544]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,266,1499]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[153,1434,265,1500]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Antiquatortia histuroides Brown &amp; Baixeras, gen. nov., sp. nov. AMNH DR8-43. Dominican amber. a. Ventral view. Length of forewing 7 mm. b. Wing venation c. Dorsal view of forewing with tufts of erect scales. d. Papillae anales. Photos: Mark Metz. Illustration: Joaquin Baixeras." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3094741/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Fig. 2 d</figureCitation>
). There is nothing that contradicts the assignment of this specimen to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[947,1073,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
. This combination of characters, especially the raised forewing scales and somewhat elongate labial palpi, suggest that the specimen represents 
<taxonomicName box="[151,280,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
, and we provisionally assign it to that tribe. This assignment must be considered tentative because the most convincing synapomorphies of the tribe are in the genitalia and not visible in this fossil specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
